299
00:17:55,260 --> 00:17:56,620
What will South Korea do in response?

300
00:18:03,140 --> 00:18:04,440
Someone wants to attack you, right?

301
00:18:04,440 --> 00:18:06,640
So, how do you get this
person not to attack you?

302
00:18:09,680 --> 00:18:11,840
Exactly. Do you understand? Alright?

303
00:18:12,060 --> 00:18:16,000
Give them money. So, North Korea
doesn't even have to attack South Korea.

304
00:18:16,140 --> 00:18:18,240
North Korea just has to
threaten to attack South Korea.

305
00:18:18,340 --> 00:18:20,740
And South Korea will give them
a lot of money not to attack.

306
00:18:20,980 --> 00:18:24,280
Do you understand? And
by doing that, right?

307
00:18:24,540 --> 00:18:27,340
North Korea becomes richer
and more military advanced.

308
00:18:27,680 --> 00:18:29,620
South Korea just becomes poorer.

309
00:18:30,840 --> 00:18:33,280
Do you understand? And
because North Korea,

310
00:18:34,440 --> 00:18:37,180
the army is fighting in
other places like Ukraine,

311
00:18:37,540 --> 00:18:40,760
it's developing all this
experience and expertise that

312
00:18:40,760 --> 00:18:44,220
will allow it to eventually
overwhelm South Korea.

313
00:18:44,820 --> 00:18:48,240
Does it make sense? So, in
this thought experiment,

314
00:18:49,080 --> 00:18:50,760
it's possible that

315
00:18:50,760 --> 00:18:54,760
North Korea can eventually
conquer South Korea.

316
00:18:55,700 --> 00:18:58,060
Okay? Does it make sense? And

317
00:18:58,060 --> 00:19:00,800
this gives us an understanding of why

318
00:19:02,220 --> 00:19:05,660
Macedonia, Macedon, was able
to conquer all of Greece.

319
00:19:05,840 --> 00:19:10,880
Even though Macedon was by
far one of the poorest places

320
00:19:11,560 --> 00:19:13,880
in Greece at that time.

321
00:19:14,080 --> 00:19:17,380
Okay? Does that make sense?
Because the people are hungry,

322
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:19,980
united, and obedient.

323
00:19:21,060 --> 00:19:25,620
Alright? Any questions so far?

324
00:19:28,120 --> 00:19:29,560
About this? Okay?

325
00:19:29,700 --> 00:19:31,660
So, I want you to remember
these two thought experiments.

326
00:19:31,660 --> 00:19:34,260
Because they will help us
explain a lot of history.

327
00:19:34,520 --> 00:19:39,640
And I will refer to these two thought experiments
some more as we go along in the course.

328
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:41,100
Okay? Alright?

329
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:42,740
But does this make sense to you so far?

330
00:19:43,400 --> 00:19:44,720
Great. Alright.

331
00:19:45,360 --> 00:19:49,780
So now, let's focus specifically
on Philip II of Macedon.

332
00:19:49,920 --> 00:19:52,780
How was he able to conquer all of Greece?

333
00:19:53,860 --> 00:19:58,260
Given that his nation, Macedon,
was poor, weak, and divided.

334
00:19:58,440 --> 00:19:59,960
Okay? Alright.

335
00:19:59,960 --> 00:20:03,160
So, King Philip, okay?

336
00:20:03,420 --> 00:20:08,020
He was born in 383 BCE.

337
00:20:08,480 --> 00:20:10,440
Okay? And I want to talk about the world

338
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:13,080
of Greece and

339
00:20:13,080 --> 00:20:16,180
Macedon at the time of his birth.

340
00:20:23,060 --> 00:20:25,240
Okay. So, around this time,

341
00:20:25,960 --> 00:20:29,340
there are three major powers in Greece.

342
00:20:29,340 --> 00:20:31,400
Okay? There's Athens.

343
00:20:32,580 --> 00:20:35,280
Remember that even though Athens
lost the Peloponnesian War,

344
00:20:36,040 --> 00:20:40,120
it's still very wealthy and it still
has the best navy in all of Greece.

345
00:20:40,220 --> 00:20:41,920
Okay? So, it's still a major power.

346
00:20:42,520 --> 00:20:45,220
Then you have Sparta,

347
00:20:45,860 --> 00:20:49,380
which for most of Greek history
was considered the best military.

348
00:20:49,700 --> 00:20:52,880
Right? And then you have... Sorry.

349
00:20:54,100 --> 00:20:58,470
Let me try to use another...

350
00:20:58,470 --> 00:21:00,570
Okay. So, the map.

351
00:21:00,750 --> 00:21:04,330
Okay? So, this is Sparta
here to the south.

352
00:21:04,530 --> 00:21:08,730
This is Athens. And then to the
north is a place called Thebes.

353
00:21:08,910 --> 00:21:11,250
And what's interesting is at this time,

354
00:21:11,410 --> 00:21:13,810
Thebes has become the
most dominant military

355
00:21:15,250 --> 00:21:19,110
in Greece. Primarily
because Sparta and Athens

356
00:21:20,170 --> 00:21:22,510
decimated each other during
the Peloponnesian War.

357
00:21:22,690 --> 00:21:25,770
Okay? So, because of
the war, Thebes has...

358
00:21:28,410 --> 00:21:31,790
became the dominant power
in Greece at this time.

359
00:21:32,390 --> 00:21:36,290
Okay. And then to the
far north is Macedon.

360
00:21:36,310 --> 00:21:40,650
Okay? The Kingdom of Macedon. Now,

361
00:21:40,650 --> 00:21:43,230
Macedon is very poor, weak, and divided.

362
00:21:43,470 --> 00:21:45,250
So, let me explain why it is.

363
00:21:45,670 --> 00:21:47,750
First of all, it has a geography problem.

364
00:21:49,050 --> 00:21:53,670
The nation is divided between
agricultural farmland to the south

365
00:21:53,670 --> 00:21:55,130
and mountains.

366
00:21:56,150 --> 00:21:57,710
And then to the north.

367
00:21:58,010 --> 00:22:01,510
Okay? So, most of its land
can't even grow crops.

368
00:22:02,190 --> 00:22:06,830
And where it can grow crops,
its farmers are just peasants.

369
00:22:06,890 --> 00:22:09,650
Okay? Now, the problem is that

370
00:22:09,650 --> 00:22:12,510
there are lots of tribes in the mountains.

371
00:22:12,970 --> 00:22:15,810
And the way they make their
living usually is by coming

372
00:22:15,810 --> 00:22:18,150
and raiding your farmland.

373
00:22:18,570 --> 00:22:20,950
And there's nothing that
you can do about it because

374
00:22:20,950 --> 00:22:23,770
if you go chase them, they
go back to the mountains.

375
00:22:23,870 --> 00:22:26,290
Okay? So, that's the first problem.

376
00:22:26,450 --> 00:22:28,970
The economy is very divided.

377
00:22:29,270 --> 00:22:33,550
And it's very... And the people
don't have that many resources.

378
00:22:33,750 --> 00:22:36,370
Okay? That's the first
problem. Second problem is

379
00:22:38,150 --> 00:22:42,210
Macedon is completely
surrounded by hostile powers.

380
00:22:43,050 --> 00:22:47,370
Okay? So, you have the
Kingdom of Phrase over here.

381
00:22:47,830 --> 00:22:49,950
And that's a long -term enemy.

382
00:22:50,150 --> 00:22:51,870
And you have Illyria over here.

383
00:22:52,250 --> 00:22:55,570
Okay? And these are
warlike mountainous people

384
00:22:56,310 --> 00:22:57,590
who live in fortresses.

385
00:22:57,590 --> 00:22:59,210
It's almost impossible to invade them.

386
00:22:59,610 --> 00:23:01,910
And it's easy for them
to come and attack you.

387
00:23:02,050 --> 00:23:03,490
Okay? So, they're a huge problem.

388
00:23:04,030 --> 00:23:06,350
To the south is a place called Phycelae.

389
00:23:08,550 --> 00:23:12,270
And they have one of the
best militaries in Greece.

390
00:23:12,410 --> 00:23:14,370
Okay? They're known for their
cavalry, their horsemen.

391
00:23:15,530 --> 00:23:18,230
And then, of course, you also
have Thebes, Athens, and Sparta,

392
00:23:18,670 --> 00:23:22,370
which also want to play a
role in controlling Macedon.

393
00:23:22,370 --> 00:23:25,470
Okay? And over here, of course,

394
00:23:25,630 --> 00:23:27,530
across the sea is called Persia.

395
00:23:28,590 --> 00:23:33,170
And for some of its history, Macedon
was actually a province of Persia.

396
00:23:33,230 --> 00:23:36,370
Okay? Persia actually conquered
or subjugated Macedon.

397
00:23:38,550 --> 00:23:44,370
So, Macedon is always being
threatened by a more superior power.

398
00:23:44,670 --> 00:23:46,370
And it keeps on losing these wars.

399
00:23:46,510 --> 00:23:49,770
Okay? The third problem it has is

400
00:23:49,770 --> 00:23:51,710
that it's a kingdom.

401
00:23:51,710 --> 00:23:55,590
It has a king. And the
king has many, many wives.

402
00:23:56,310 --> 00:23:57,610
And why would this be a problem?

403
00:24:01,810 --> 00:24:05,570
Exactly. Okay? There are a lot of sons,
and they fight over who will be king.

404
00:24:06,410 --> 00:24:08,370
And the thing is that

405
00:24:08,370 --> 00:24:14,050
these sons are always supported by
another foreign power. Okay? Because

406
00:24:14,050 --> 00:24:19,910
the foreign powers want Macedon
to be always in conflict.

407
00:24:19,910 --> 00:24:21,310
Okay?

408
00:24:21,530 --> 00:24:25,190
So, for most of its
history, Macedon was poor,

409
00:24:25,450 --> 00:24:26,870
weak, and divided.

410
00:24:28,670 --> 00:24:31,610
And then Philip II changes all that.

411
00:24:32,210 --> 00:24:34,550
So, he's born in 383.

412
00:24:35,210 --> 00:24:38,390
And then from 369 to 365,

413
00:24:38,670 --> 00:24:41,590
for about five years,
he's a hostage in Thebes.

414
00:24:41,830 --> 00:24:45,170
The reason why is Macedon
lost the war to Thebes.

415
00:24:45,630 --> 00:24:49,890
And to ensure that Macedon does
not rebel against the Thracians,

416
00:24:50,630 --> 00:24:52,350
Macedon had to send hostages.

417
00:24:52,970 --> 00:24:55,650
And so, Philip was a hostage in Thebes.

418
00:24:55,830 --> 00:24:58,410
But he's a prince. So, he's treated very,

419
00:24:58,490 --> 00:25:02,190
very nicely in Thebes.

420
00:25:02,410 --> 00:25:04,990
And he can do whatever
he wants. The thing that

421
00:25:04,990 --> 00:25:06,670
he wants to do is he wants to

422
00:25:06,670 --> 00:25:10,750
understand why Thebes
is the dominant military

423
00:25:10,750 --> 00:25:12,850
power in Greece at this time.

424
00:25:13,310 --> 00:25:16,210
And he learns from the
best Theban generals.

425
00:25:16,490 --> 00:25:18,630
They become his mentors.

426
00:25:18,630 --> 00:25:21,230
Okay? So,

427
00:25:21,290 --> 00:25:23,170
what makes Thebes so

428
00:25:23,170 --> 00:25:28,030
effective is the idea of
the sacred ban of Thebes.

429
00:25:31,150 --> 00:25:34,590
This is the secret to the power of Thebes.

430
00:25:34,830 --> 00:25:37,690
Okay? These are 300 soldiers

431
00:25:37,690 --> 00:25:38,990
who

432
00:25:38,990 --> 00:25:43,310
spend every day training to
be the best soldiers they can.

433
00:25:44,610 --> 00:25:48,610
And in many ways, they're
like special forces.

434
00:25:48,630 --> 00:25:50,850
Okay? And

435
00:25:50,850 --> 00:25:53,550
this is modeled off Sparta, right?

436
00:25:53,770 --> 00:25:55,190
The difference is this.

437
00:25:55,210 --> 00:25:58,650
The difference is in
Sparta, only citizens,

438
00:25:58,850 --> 00:26:00,530
only aristocrats can be soldiers.

439
00:26:01,310 --> 00:26:05,590
But in Thebes, these 300
people were volunteers.

440
00:26:06,010 --> 00:26:10,770
They were commoners who
wanted to be soldiers. And so,

441
00:26:10,830 --> 00:26:16,530
the first thing Philip learned in
Thebes is anyone can be a soldier.

442
00:26:16,710 --> 00:26:19,570
Not just the rich. Okay?
With proper training,

443
00:26:19,790 --> 00:26:22,850
anyone can learn to be a great soldier.

444
00:26:24,570 --> 00:26:27,870
That's the first thing he learned.
Second thing he learned is when

445
00:26:27,870 --> 00:26:33,170
you have an elite group of soldiers, it's
really about how to use them effectively. Okay?

446
00:26:33,290 --> 00:26:39,190
So, the traditional warfare in Greece
at this time is called a phallax.

447
00:26:39,350 --> 00:26:41,530
Right? The hoplite phallax.

448
00:26:42,230 --> 00:26:43,910
Okay? So, remember, it
is like a moving wall.

449
00:26:44,250 --> 00:26:46,530
They move together slowly.

450
00:26:46,530 --> 00:26:48,950
Slowly. And try to crush the enemy.

451
00:26:49,170 --> 00:26:53,750
Okay? The innovation
the Thebans did was say,

452
00:26:53,930 --> 00:26:56,210
we're going to do a slant.

453
00:26:56,370 --> 00:26:58,750
Okay? The reason why
is when you do a slant,

454
00:26:58,890 --> 00:27:01,970
you can put the 300 sacred bands

455
00:27:01,970 --> 00:27:06,190
first against the best
soldiers of the enemy.

456
00:27:06,370 --> 00:27:09,550
Okay? And we know that in a fair fight,

457
00:27:09,830 --> 00:27:15,750
these 300 will always destroy
the first soldiers of the enemy.

458
00:27:15,750 --> 00:27:19,570
But when you do that, there's
a massive psychological effect.

459
00:27:20,930 --> 00:27:24,750
And so, what happens is the
phallax breaks formation.

460
00:27:25,190 --> 00:27:28,910
And if the phallax breaks formation, and
people start running away, they're all dead.

461
00:27:29,230 --> 00:27:30,570
Okay? So, that

462
00:27:30,570 --> 00:27:35,890
is the major innovation
of Thebes at this time.

463
00:27:36,310 --> 00:27:38,310
Okay? And

464
00:27:38,310 --> 00:27:41,390
from the best generals of Thebes, okay,

465
00:27:41,530 --> 00:27:45,090
Philip understood the
importance of discipline.

466
00:27:47,690 --> 00:27:49,110
He understood the importance
of discipline in an army.

467
00:27:50,450 --> 00:27:51,790
And this is new. Okay?

468
00:27:51,870 --> 00:27:54,630
Because in Greece, remember,
the Spaniards had discipline,

469
00:27:54,870 --> 00:27:57,830
but most armies, like the Athenians,
they were citizen soldiers.

470
00:27:58,070 --> 00:28:01,030
They did this for fun. They
did this as a civic duty.

471
00:28:01,330 --> 00:28:02,590
They did this part -time.

472
00:28:02,690 --> 00:28:06,270
Okay? So, they weren't really
training when they weren't fighting.

473
00:28:07,270 --> 00:28:09,150
Now, when you train,
you develop discipline.

474
00:28:09,790 --> 00:28:14,130
With discipline, you have
three major strengths.

475
00:28:14,130 --> 00:28:16,610
Okay? The first major strength that

476
00:28:16,610 --> 00:28:23,190
you have is the idea
of mobility, speed. And

477
00:28:23,190 --> 00:28:29,010
what this means is your army can
march much faster than other armies.

478
00:28:29,950 --> 00:28:32,730
Okay? So, maybe this is important

479
00:28:32,730 --> 00:28:36,910
because maybe you want to attack a city.

480
00:28:36,990 --> 00:28:39,570
Right? If you get there really fast, and

481
00:28:39,570 --> 00:28:41,410
you're able to siege
a city and destroy it,

482
00:28:41,610 --> 00:28:44,430
the city cannot ask for reinforcements.

483
00:28:44,430 --> 00:28:46,110
Okay? Because reinforcements
will come too slowly.

484
00:28:46,550 --> 00:28:47,990
Does that make sense? Okay?

485
00:28:48,090 --> 00:28:51,870
So, this is a major innovation,
the idea of mobility.

486
00:28:52,150 --> 00:28:54,270
Okay? Second is the idea of coordination.

487
00:28:57,330 --> 00:29:00,570
Coordination. So, different military
units are able to work together.

488
00:29:01,270 --> 00:29:03,970
And this is really important. So,

489
00:29:03,970 --> 00:29:05,490
in Greece at this time,

490
00:29:05,650 --> 00:29:10,330
there are maybe two different land forces.

491
00:29:10,430 --> 00:29:12,730
Right? There's a phalanx,
and there's a cavalry.

492
00:29:12,830 --> 00:29:14,490
Right? And they do their own thing.

493
00:29:14,670 --> 00:29:16,310
Okay? But with discipline,

